<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#5B96D8">
<td width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Author</b></font></td><td width="80%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="#ffffff" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: bold;"><b>Discussion</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>addowns</b>
<br>31 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>I strongly disagree</b>
<br>
<p>I have a different opinion about the published materials--I have always looked at Earthdawn guides not as rules supplements, but as mood and concept supplements.  Guides like _The Ork Nation of Cara Fahd_ and _BLood Wood_ were great because they revealed the secrets of those lands--not because they gave me new rules to use in my next campaign.<p></p>This doesn't mean that I always agreed with everything that they have written, but have you agreed with every book put out by Wizards of the Coast or Steve Jackson Games?  If you don't want but 5% of the material, find one of the 50 people you've met and photocopy it!  Don't keep me from gathering ideas for adventures in Skypoint or Throal, just because you think that 95% of the book was lousy.<p></p>Here's a tip--read sourcebooks like novels or history text, not straight supplemental materials.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>robertsvard</b>
<br>30 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>I have played ED since 1995 and I daresay I have bought, borrowed or read every single ED book that has ever been published, including some of the more obscure net project books. <p></p>Now, the first thing that sprung to my mind, was that I only ever (during 7 years of intense GMing and playing in a number of highly diversed ED campaigns) seemed to encounter/use about 2% of the material from all the books. <p></p>I was simply overwhelmed by the vast amount of bad writing, unrealized storylines, failed plots, un-epic epicness and worst of all, the wonderfully inane "mythos" of the whole ED universe. I love ED, I really do, but I think that what killed it was the amount of crap that was published, in a manner that totally diluted the value of the core world. From what I first new about Barsaive in the world section of the 1st ED rule book, to all the completely unnecessary stuff that was published after awhile. <p></p>Who ever used the weird legends in ED Legends? Who ever forced their players to memorize all the adept meta-mythos in the Adepts way? Who ever used 5% of the horrors featured in the books? Who could ever play a single adventure without major rewriting of the plot?<p></p>I recognize the idea behind it all: to publish and provide to players a vast amount of material to choose from and so build their own campaigns out of this material. But in reality it just served to dilute the ED brand and confused players as to wich book was ever worth buying. Inevitably every book contained a gem, but who wants to fork out a considerable amount of cash for all the nonsense that followed in the books? Now, I have only met about 40-50 different ED players, but many seemed to share my feelings.<p></p>Too much material, not enough quality. Too few gems, too far spread out. <p></p>So when I saw the publishing list today my jaw dropped. "oh no, they are doing it again."<p></p>If I can't appeal to your taste, I should at least be able to appeal to your sense of economics - who will buy these sourcebooks, the total being worth something like a smaller car? Is there truly a market for it? Is it all really that good? Is all the material really useful? Publish new books with a concentrated material instead of just rehashing the old stuff. Give us the cream, and write new stuff to replace the 95% junk ratio of before. You have the power to do this! <p></p>And one thing that always bothered me in ED, if the world was supposed to be an ancient version of our own, why are all the rivers, coastlines and continents EXACTLY parallel to todays Earth? Why not to the earth of 25 000 years ago? It would make more sense...<p></p>Sorry about my crappy English. I'm not a native speaker, but who is in this day and age? :)<p></p>Robert</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>PatB</b>
<br>30 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>Hey Robert,<p></p>I'm kind of agreeing with most of your points, and to name a few...<br>- The Adepts book: 4/5 blablabla, 1/5 useful material.<br>- The races books: could easily be in a single book.<br>- Dragons and horrors, again two books (if the first could come out one day) that could be easily joined together.  We need information, but these beings are so powerful that you don't care if there are 50 or 100 of them.  10 of each, plus minions are enough, for each sides.<p></p>On the other and although you are right about advantures, I believe we need them for ideas, not just for simply playing them because they have to fit with your PCs.  That's why I liked the idea that FASA was using at one point with ShadowRun, or how Living Room Game made their first ever adventure book: the adventures are written as guidelines.  The GM decides the encounters, the level of difficulty, the legend awards, etc.<p></p>Look at it this way, it saves up some space for other material in the same book, like another adventure, or even additional game material.<p></p>Lastly and personaly, I simply just love the ED rules, but not the world.  That's why my group decided to use another world instead, a great world accompanied by lousy/crappy game rules, Dark Sun from AD&amp;D.<p></p>We've been at it since 1995, removing some ED stuff (sorry, no orks, trolls, etc.), adding more (like half-giants, muls, etc.), and changing some (the sky raider is now a desert raider and the air sailor a silt sailor).<p></p>Bottom line, and to quote you, "Too much material, not enough quality. Too few gems, too far spread out."<p></p>My two cents.<p></p>Pat B</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Saria</b>
<br>30 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>Why not to the earth of 25 000 years ago? It would make more sense...<p></p>I have to address this part.<p></p>The Earth of Earthdawn is the Earth of approximately 5000 years ago (3113 BC marks the end of the 4th world).  FASA put this forth in a short story in the Shadowrun setting by Tom Dowd (<a target="_blank" href="">Humans &amp; the Cycle of Magic</a><a target="_blank" href="http://www.srrpg.com/fiction/fiction1.shtml">Humans &amp; the Cycle of Magic</a> on the official SR Webpage).<p></p>Geologically speaking, not much is new in the world.  There's no reason to have them be much different.  Sure, rivers would have changed with erosion, same with the coastlines.  But still, not much.  The coastlines have always fit together, that's where the theory of continental drift came from.<p></p>Sorry, that geology degree comes peeking out from time to time.<p></p>Lady Saria<br>http://www.ladysaria.com</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
