<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>LadsoBarsaive</b>
<br>31 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>Speaking as someone who's played ED for most of the time it's been out, and who plays with people who loved ED from Day One, I have to strongly disagree with you...<p></p>The game designers cleared stated in the rules, and I'm paraphrasing, "take the world and make it your own. The rules are a guide..."<p></p>For a game that takes place 5-7,000 years before our own, the amount of reverse extrapolation that had to take place was enourmous, and all hangs together reasonably well. An "inane mythos"? Does that take into account the disparate viewpoints of the Theran Noble, to the Blood Warder, to the Crystal Raider, to the Urupan-born Illusionist that each live in the ED world and have experienced it in their own way? <p></p>The ED Legends book was a great way to get the flavor of the world, and ideas on how to make magic items, write ED style, and what the whole idea is behind "legend". I was never forced to memorize anything out of Adept's Way, but one of my favorite characters came from some of the flavor text and additional rules in the book (an Explorer Scout). A character I'm running now that is the son of a character I played for 8 years also grew from ideas that came in reading that sourcebook.<p></p>Did I like everything in the Theran Sourcebook? No, I thought the whole Talean section was poo, but I liked the book overall. The Cara Fahd and Crystal Raider sourcebooks were invaluable, front to back, for playing in entire campagins I participated in, from local flavor to scenario ideas, to character concepts.<p></p>I wouldn't want to go against more than 5% of the Horrors in the FASA Horrors book. To this day that book gives me the creeps, because of how it's written and what it implies in the ED world of the Horrors. And the few Horrors from that book the GMs ran us against in a proper fashion (no Verjigorm-is-my-bitach silliness here) were thought provoking, character threatening role-playing experiences.<p></p>If you have to re-write the plot in a module to fit your campaign, so what? I'd rather do that then read verbatim out of a book just to run something...and customizing adventures for players is the sign of the GM who's got their buunda together...<p></p>Perhaps FASA dropped plots or had some continuity errors...on the whole, one can find all manner of gems in the bulk of the ED material, from metaplot to game flavor to character concepts to adventure hooks. All ya have to do is look.<p></p>Where I think ED went wrong, originally, is when the folks at FASA dropped it in favor of Vor, Crimson Skies, and Crucible. That left lots of material unpublished, and many gamers in the lurch until LRG came along to pick up ED again. And now RedBrick is here to pick up the pieces again, AGAIN...<p></p>Now is the opportunity, where Redbrick is holding out a seat to gamers to contribute to the ED game world, if you want to. Ultimately, we gamers COLLECT the gaming material to play in a game world. If you're not interested in buying, and don't think it's worth playing...why be involved at all? If it's all about economics, would you really be a gamer? Would you ever take a chance on a new game system without a guaranteed positive ROI? <p></p>To me, that's not gaming, it's just bean counting. Now is the time to participate and add to the ED world.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>LadsoBarsaive</b>
<br>31 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>And, when I last checked, I can't book a flight to Thera, or hang out by Death's Sea or the Liaj Jungle...so it would seem that there are changes to the shape of the world...<p></p>Christopher</p>
</font></td>
