<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Tarliman</b>
<br>31 October 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn?</b>
<br>
<p>I've used many of the legends in ED: Legends of Barsaive and the Book of Exploration. Mind you, I wrote four of the BofE legends, so of course I've used my own material in gaming. <p></p>To me, the legends, the backstory, the flavor text, is what sets ED apart from other game systems. There's more depth of culture, more flavor to the gameworld, and more possibilities in actually playing the role of your character. I strongly dislike games that bring out rules supplement after rules supplement, not naming Names as that would be impolitic. For a roleplaying game, I want the emphasis to be on roleplaying, and that requires background information. The Denizens books are some of my favorite gaming material of all time. They add so much depth to the Name-giver races that I'm hard pressed to think of a supplement that has enhanced my game more, except maybe Robin Laws' masterpiece, Throal. <p></p>I have to ask you this: If you find the writing and line development so distasteful, why do you have anything to do with Earthdawn in the first place? Perhaps there are other game systems that would appeal more to your preferences.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
